Use MSTest's **data-driven tests** to collapse all those methods into two parameterized ones. Replace `[TestMethod]` + `[DataRow]` (or `[DynamicData]` for non-constant values) so each new case is just one line:

```csharp
using Microsoft.VisualStudio.TestTools.UnitTesting;

namespace Validation.Tests;

[TestClass]
public sealed class InputValidatorTests
{
    private static IEnumerable<object?[]> InvalidInputCases =>
    [
        [null,                  "Input cannot be empty"],
        ["",                    "Input cannot be empty"],
        ["   ",                 "Input cannot be empty"],
        ["ab",                  "Input must be at least 3 characters"],
        [new string('x', 256), "Input must not exceed 255 characters"],
        ["hello<script>",       "Input contains invalid characters"],
    ];

    private static IEnumerable<object?[]> ValidInputCases =>
    [
        ["abc"],
        ["hello-world"],
        [new string('a', 255)],
    ];

    [DataTestMethod]
    [DynamicData(nameof(InvalidInputCases))]
    public void Validate_InvalidInput_ReturnsFalse(string? input, string expectedError)
    {
        var result = new InputValidator().Validate(input);

        Assert.IsFalse(result.IsValid);
        Assert.AreEqual(expectedError, result.ErrorMessage);
    }

    [DataTestMethod]
    [DynamicData(nameof(ValidInputCases))]
    public void Validate_ValidInput_ReturnsTrue(string input)
    {
        var result = new InputValidator().Validate(input);

        Assert.IsTrue(result.IsValid);
        Assert.IsNull(result.ErrorMessage);
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`[DynamicData]`** pulls test cases from a static property — needed here because `new string('x', 256)` isn't a compile-time constant. For simple constant cases, `[DataRow("ab", "must be at least 3...")]` works too.
- Adding a new case = adding one line to the array. No new method needed.
- Each case still shows as a **separate test** in the runner, so failures are easy to identify.
